<subSubSection lastPageId="199" lastPageNumber="200" pageId="198" pageNumber="199" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="198.[151,1437,1161,2017]" lastBlockId="199.[151,1436,153,287]" lastPageId="199" lastPageNumber="200" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,810,1161,1188]" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Subfamily diagnosis based on adult male morphology</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[828,963,1162,1188]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 78" captionStart-1="FIGURE 79" captionStart-2="FIGURE 80" captionStart-3="FIGURE 81" captionStart-4="FIGURE 82" captionStart-5="FIGURE 83" captionStart-6="FIGURE 84" captionStartId-0="201.[151,250,1901,1926]" captionStartId-1="203.[151,250,1889,1914]" captionStartId-2="206.[151,250,1954,1979]" captionStartId-3="208.[151,250,1798,1823]" captionStartId-4="210.[151,250,1868,1893]" captionStartId-5="213.[151,250,1775,1800]" captionStartId-6="216.[151,250,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox-0="[153,1426,246,1877]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1427,322,1865]" captionTargetBox-2="[163,1436,247,1929]" captionTargetBox-3="[161,1426,193,1772]" captionTargetBox-4="[160,1429,427,1843]" captionTargetBox-5="[163,1425,190,1750]" captionTargetBox-6="[171,1420,189,1920]" captionTargetId-0="figure@201.[151,1436,237,1877]" captionTargetId-1="figure@203.[151,1436,309,1865]" captionTargetId-2="figure@206.[151,1436,237,1929]" captionTargetId-3="figure@208.[151,1436,181,1772]" captionTargetId-4="figure@210.[151,1436,417,1843]" captionTargetId-5="figure@213.[151,1436,181,1750]" captionTargetId-6="figure@216.[161,1426,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId-0="201" captionTargetPageId-1="203" captionTargetPageId-2="206" captionTargetPageId-3="208" captionTargetPageId-4="210" captionTargetPageId-5="213" captionTargetPageId-6="216" captionText-0="FIGURE 78. Aclerda arundinariae McConnell. Macropterous male. (Aclerdidae, Aclerdinae). Where A=cranial apophysis, P=loculate pore and R=dermal reticulations on ocular sclerite." captionText-1="FIGURE 79. Aclerda distorta Green. Macropterous male. (Aclerdidae, Aclerdinae). Where A=cranial apophysis, E=loculate pore and R=dermal reticulations on ocular sclerite." captionText-2="FIGURE 80. Aclerda tillandsiae Howell. Macropterous male. (Aclerdidae, Aclerdinae)." captionText-3="FIGURE 81. Aclerda tokionis Cockerell. Macropterous male. (Aclerdidae, Aclerdinae). Where A=cranial apophysis." captionText-4="FIGURE 82. Aclerda sp. A. Michoacán, Mexico. Macropterous male. (Aclerdidae, Aclerdinae). Where A=cranial apophysis, C=loculate pore, D=simple pore and R=dermal reticulations on ocular sclerite." captionText-5="FIGURE 83. Aclerda sp. B. South Dakota, USA. Macropterous male. (Aclerdidae, Aclerdinae). Where A=cranial apophysis, C=loculate pore, D=simple pore and R=dermal reticulations on ocular sclerite." captionText-6="FIGURE 84. Lecanaclerda macropoda Hodgson &amp; Millar. Macropterous male. (Aclerdidae. Aclerdinae). Where A=cranial apophysis, D=simple pore, K=apex of antennal capitate seta and R=dermal reticulations on ocular sclerite." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3774334" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3774336" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3774338" figureDoi-3="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3774340" figureDoi-4="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3774342" figureDoi-5="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3774344" figureDoi-6="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3774346" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3774334/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3774336/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/3774338/files/figure.png" httpUri-3="https://zenodo.org/record/3774340/files/figure.png" httpUri-4="https://zenodo.org/record/3774342/files/figure.png" httpUri-5="https://zenodo.org/record/3774344/files/figure.png" httpUri-6="https://zenodo.org/record/3774346/files/figure.png" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Figs 78–84</figureCitation>
). Body size small to moderate; antennae about half total length of body; body with few setae, possibly entirely hs; fs on limbs generally easy to differentiate from hs. 
<emphasis box="[253,904,1234,1261]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Body often with frequent small convex pores (cp) dorsally</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[918,989,1234,1260]" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Head.</emphasis>
Genae generally unsclerotised; without reticulations; usually with 1 pair hs genal setae. Ocelli present and generally distinct. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Ocular sclerite with polygonal reticulations</emphasis>
. Postocular ridge short. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Postoccipital ridge absent. Cranial apophysis extending far forward on head, between ventral simple eyes, on the end of long preoral ridges</emphasis>
; 
<emphasis box="[889,1320,1342,1368]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">postoral tentorial bridge pronounced.</emphasis>
Antennae 10-segmented; with short fs and an occasional hs; antennal bristles apparently undifferentiated; apical segment with 3 capitate setae. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[399,521,1414,1440]" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Prothorax</emphasis>
usually with 1 or 2 pairs of prosternal setae; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">small convex pores (cp) present or absent on dorsum</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[370,522,1450,1476]" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Mesothorax:</emphasis>
Prescutum small. Membranous area of scutum quite small, about twice as wide as long; 
<emphasis box="[246,580,1486,1512]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">with 0–2 pairs hs scutal setae</emphasis>
. Scutellar setae (scls) present or absent. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Area within mesopostnotum usually with a large sclerite</emphasis>
, (possibly absent on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Howell. Macropterous" authorityYear="1972" box="[623,773,1522,1549]" class="Insecta" family="Aclerdidae" genus="Aclerda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="198" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tillandsiae">
<emphasis box="[623,773,1522,1549]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">A. tillandsiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hodgson &amp; Millar. Macropterous" authorityYear="2002" box="[831,989,1522,1548]" class="Insecta" family="Aclerdidae" genus="Lecanaclerda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="198" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macropoda">
<emphasis box="[831,989,1522,1548]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">L. macropoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Basisternum with median ridge weak or absent; without basisternal setae; 
<emphasis box="[561,835,1558,1584]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">lateropleurite very large</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[849,1363,1558,1584]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">often extending anteriorly as well as laterally</emphasis>
; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">furca basally rather short but broad</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[509,1071,1594,1620]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Mesothoracic spiracles each with 0–5 disc-pores,</emphasis>
each with 3–6 loculi. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Metathorax:</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[207,578,1630,1656]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">postmesospiracular setae absent.</emphasis>
Metathorax with a pair of hs metatergal seta. Dorsal part of metapleural ridge absent. 
<emphasis box="[238,1089,1666,1692]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">
Metathoracic spiracle placed more posteriorly than on most 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rubsaamen" authorityYear="1899" box="[930,1089,1666,1692]" infraOrder="Coccomorpha" pageId="198" pageNumber="6" rank="infraOrder">Coccomorpha</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[1104,1326,1666,1692]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">with 0–6 disc-pores</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Anterior metasternal setae and posterior metasternal setae absent.</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[811,887,1701,1728]" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Wings</emphasis>
without alar lobes or alar setae. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Hamulohalteres absent.</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[240,285,1738,1764]" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Leg</emphasis>
setae usually all hs or spur-like. Trochanter each with campaniform sensilla in a line. Tibia with one large apical spur. Tarsal spurs absent or barely differentiated; 
<emphasis box="[831,1187,1774,1800]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">tarsal campaniform pore absent</emphasis>
. Claws without a denticle. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[214,331,1809,1836]" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Abdomen</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[339,852,1810,1837]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">usually with small convex pores (cp) dorsally</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[867,1428,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Abdominal sternites and tergites all with sclerites</emphasis>
; pleurites on segments IV–VII generally showing varying degrees of sclerotisation. 
<emphasis box="[1072,1325,1846,1872]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Abdominal setae all hs</emphasis>
. Segment VIII tergite sclerotised; caudal extension generally absent; pleural area usually with a seta at least half as long as penial sheath; 
<emphasis box="[313,679,1918,1944]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">without ante-anal setae medially</emphasis>
; sternite sclerotised, forming anterior section of penial sheath, with strongly sclerotised lateral margins (absent on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hodgson &amp; Millar. Macropterous" authorityYear="2002" box="[670,825,1954,1980]" class="Insecta" family="Aclerdidae" genus="Lecanaclerda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="198" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macropoda">
<emphasis box="[670,825,1954,1980]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">L. macropoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); without setae. 
<emphasis box="[1010,1369,1954,1980]" italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Glandular pouch usually absent</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Sternite VIII strongly sclerotised and plate-like, often with lateral margins ridge-like.</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1068,1273,1989,2016]" pageId="198" pageNumber="199">Genital segments</emphasis>
: Penial sheath rather short, 
<emphasis box="[301,1030,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="199" pageNumber="200">articulating anteriorly with sclerotised sternite of segment VIII</emphasis>
; segment IX fused to style; penial sheath broadest anteriorly, narrowing abruptly to a blunt, narrow, rather parallel-sided style. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="199" pageNumber="200">Anus surrounded by a sclerotised ring.</emphasis>
Aedeagus (aed) rather short but generally exceptionally broad, approximately parallel-sided. Many species with a long membranous extrusion from end of style, possibly an endophallus.
</paragraph>
